{{short description|3rd-century BC Greek tyrant of Sicyon}} {{Infobox royalty | type = majesty | consort = | name = Abantidas | title = [[Tyrant]] of [[Sicyon]] | more = | image = | alt = | caption = | succession = | moretext = | reign = | predecessor = | pre-type = | successor = | suc-type = | reign1 = 264 BC-252 BC | reign-type1 = Reign | predecessor1 = [[Cleinias (disambiguation)|Cleinias]] | pre-type1 = Predecessor | successor1 = [[Paseas]] | suc-type1 = Successor | succession2 = 252 BC | house = | house-type = | father = [[Paseas]] | mother = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 252 BC | death_place = [[Sicyon]] }}
'''Abantidas''' (in [[Greek language|Greek]] '''Ἀβαντίδας'''), the son of [[Paseas]], became [[Tyranny|tyrant]] of the [[ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[city-state]] of [[Sicyon]] after murdering [[Cleinias of Sicyon|Cleinias]], the father of [[Aratus of Sicyon|Aratus]], 264 BC.{{r|plut_2_paus_2.8}} After the assassination, Abantidas had the remaining friends and relations of Cleinias banished or put to death; Aratus, who was then only seven years old, narrowly escaped death by fleeing into the house of Soso, Abantidas' sister, who happened to be married to Prophantus, the late Cleinias' brother.<ref>http://classics.mit.edu/Plutarch/aratus.html</ref>{{r|plut_2}} Abantidas was fond of literature, and was accustomed to attending the [[Philosophy|philosophical]] discussions of [[Deinias of Argos]] and [[Aristotle the Dialectician|Aristotle, the dialectician]], in the [[agora]] of Sicyon: on one of these occasions, with the complicity of the two [[Rhetoric|rhetors]], he was murdered by his enemies in 252. He was succeeded as tyrant of Sicyon by his father, Paseas, who was later put to death by [[Nicocles (Sicyon)|Nicocles]].{{r|plut_3}}{{clarify|reason=was he killed by Nicocles or did Nicocles have him killed by someone else?|date=November 2018}}
