'''Alan III de Rohan''' ({{circa|1135/40}} – 1195), was the son of [[Alan II, Viscount of Rohan]].<ref>Père Anselme, M. Potier de Courcy (ed.) ''Histoire généalogique et chronologique de la maison royale de France'', volume IV, 1868, p. 50.</ref> He was the 3rd Viscount of Rohan and Lord of Corlay.<ref>Anatole de Barthélémy, ''Le Château de Corlay'' in ''Revue de Bretagne et de Vendée'' 1865, pp 71-77, 89-102, 385-397.</ref>

== Life ==

He married [[Constance of Penthièvre]], daughter of [[Alan, 1st Earl of Richmond|Alan of Penthièvre]] and [[Bertha, Duchess of Brittany]].<ref>Père Anselme, M. Potier de Courcy (ed.) ''Histoire généalogique et chronologique de la maison royale de France'', volume IV, 1868, p. 50-51.</ref> They had six children:
* [[Alan IV, Viscount of Rohan|Alan IV]], (c. 1166 - 1205);
* William (died after 1205);
* Josselin (died in 1251), Lord of [[Noyal]], regent of the Viscounty of Rohan in 1235 married Maude of Montfort, [[House of Montfort-sur-Meu|Lady of Montfort and of Boutavan]] (1235-1279);<ref>Josselin may also be the son of Alan and his second wife Françoise of Corbey</ref>
* Margaret, who married [[Harvey I, Lord of Léon|Harvey I]], [[Lordship of Léon|Lord of Léon]];
* Alix;
* Constance, who married Odo of Pontchâteau

Alan III and his wife Constance built the [[Abbaye Notre-Dame de Bon-Repos]] on 23 June 1184.

Constance died at an unknown date after 23 June 1184 and Alan married Françoise of Corbey.<ref>Morice, Pierre-Hyacinthe, [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1041641k/f415.image  ''Mémoires pour servir de preuves à l'histoire ecclésiastique et civile de Bretagne''], 1750, volume 1, p 698.</ref>

