A '''dynasty trust''' is a [[Trust law|trust]] designed to avoid or minimize [[Estate tax in the United States|estate taxes]] being applied to great family wealth with each transfer to subsequent generations.<ref>{{cite news | last = Madoff | first = Ray | title = America Builds an Aristocracy | publisher = [[The New York Times]] | date = 11 July 2010 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/12/opinion/12madoff.html | accessdate = 2011-05-28 }}</ref> By holding assets in the trust and making well-defined distributions to each generation, the entire wealth of the trust is not subject to estate taxes with the passage of each generation.
Dynasty trusts in the United States are the combined result of the imposition of the [[generation-skipping transfer tax]] upon trusts that attempted to bypass transferring all assets to children, and the repeal of the [[rule against perpetuities]] by states attempting to attract the great wealth of such trusts.<ref>{{cite news | last = Saunders | first = Laura | title = Dynasty Trusts Under Attack | publisher = [[The Wall Street Journal]] | date = 5 March 2011 | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703752404576179031767463642 | accessdate = 2011-05-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author=Robert H. Sitkoff and Max M. Schanzenbach | title=Jurisdictional Competition for Trust Funds: An Empirical Analysis of Perpetuities and Taxes | journal=[[Yale Law Journal]] | volume=115 | year=2005 | pages=356 | ssrn = 666481 }}</ref>
