{{Infobox gridiron football person |name =Jerry Anderson |image = |birth_date =October 27, 1953 |birth_place =[[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]] |death_date ={{death date and age|1989|5|27|1953|10|27}} |death_place =Murfreesboro, Tennessee |College =[[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] |Position =[[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|Safety]] |Height_ft =5 |Height_in =11 |Weight_lbs =200 |DraftedYear =1977 |DraftedRound =4 |DraftedPick =105 |playing_years1 =1977 |playing_team1 =[[Cincinnati Bengals]] ([[National Football League|NFL]]) |playing_years2 =1978 |playing_team2 =[[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (NFL) |playing_years3 =1980–1981 |playing_team3 =[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] ([[Canadian Football League|CFL]]) |DatabaseFootball =ANDERJER01 }} '''Jerry O. Anderson''' (October 27, 1953 – May 27, 1989) was an [[American football]] [[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|safety]]. He played one season for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] and one season for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in the [[National Football League]]. He played in 14 games in [[1977 Cincinnati Bengals season|1977]] with Cincinnati and two games in [[1978 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|1978]] with Tampa Bay, but never recorded an [[interception]]. He then played for the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] in [[1980 CFL season|1980]] and [[1981 CFL season|1981]].
Following his career, he was viewed as a hero by his family and community. On May 27, 1984, he rescued some trapped motorists from floodwaters in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]. Exactly five years later, on May 27, 1989, he died attempting to save two young boys from drowning in his hometown of [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]]. On October 31, 1989, the story of his heroism and death was aired on ''[[Rescue 911]]''.<ref>{{YouTube|yv37DKcV6KI|Jerry Anderson's story on ''Rescue 911'' Part 1}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|4wkfRMBXNLs|Jerry Anderson's story on ''Rescue 911'' Part 2}}</ref>
