[[File:Mount Vernon, NYJane Doe facial reconstruction.jpg|right|thumb|170px|Westchester County Jane Doe, unidentified since 1988]] In [[New York (state)|New York]] state, there are a number of murder victims in the category of [[unidentified decedent]]s. In these cases, the murderer has never been identified.
==Ulster County John Doe==
A frozen male corpse was found on February 1, 1970 in the [[Ulster County, New York|Ulster County]] town of [[Saugerties (town), New York|Saugerties]], at the bottom of a slope near [[Platte Clove]] Road by two children who were out sledding. He was aged between 35 and 45 and had been shot four times in the back of the head. The victim was approximately {{convert|5|ft|3|in|cm}} tall and weighed about {{convert|155|lb}}. He had dark brown hair, with balding at the crown. He was wearing a tan three-quarter length raincoat over a dark green suit with faint [[Pin stripes|pinstripes]]; beneath was a blue dress shirt and black silk [[Playboy Enterprises]] tie with pajamas underneath. On his feet were gray socks and size 8{{frac|1|2}} black dress shoes covered by black Canadian-made Wings [[galoshes|rubbers]]. In his pocket he had $156 (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|156|1970}}}} in modern dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) in cash, but no identification.<ref name="THR 2016 story">{{cite news|last=Yakin|first=Heather|title=Unsolved: Police still working West Saugerties case|url=http://www.recordonline.com/news/20160925/unsolved-police-still-working-west-saugerties-case|newspaper=[[Times Herald Record]]|date=September 25, 2016|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>
He appeared to be from outside the United States, most likely [[Brazil]]. His suit has been described as "European-style". On his wrist was an Omega Seamaster wristwatch (serial number 16815714) that had been sold in a Portuguese coastal resort town. His other accessory was a gold ring whose stamp indicated it had been made in Brazil, set with an imitation [[ruby]] of Portuguese manufacture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 405UMNY|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/405umny.html|date= 22 January 2012|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> His undershirt was a Brazilian store brand, made in [[Taiwan]]; the bullets used to kill him also appeared to be a Brazilian brand.<ref name="THR 2016 story" />
The death is believed to be gang-related. Members of local organized crime groups were questioned, but never revealed who the victim was.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noble & Ready|url=http://canyouidentifyme.blogspot.com/2011/09/noble-ready.html|website=canyouidentifyme.blogspot.com|accessdate=4 December 2014|date=27 November 2011}}</ref> In 2015, investigators had the body [[exhumation|exhumed]] and sent samples for a [[DNA]] profile; so far there have been no matches to those in any database.<ref name="2016 Freeman story">{{cite news|last=Pineiro-Zucker|first=Diane|title=Police still hope to crack 46-year-old cold case of man found shot to death in West Saugerties|url=http://www.dailyfreeman.com/general-news/20160621/police-still-hope-to-crack-46-year-old-cold-case-of-man-found-shot-to-death-in-west-saugerties|newspaper=[[Daily Freeman]]|date=August 21, 2016|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>
{{anchor|Chautauqua County Jane Doe}}
==Chautauqua County Jane Doe==
On the morning of December 6, 1983, a woman's body was found by utility workers in a roadside ditch alongside eastbound [[New York State Route 17|NY 17]] (now [[Interstate 86 (east)|Interstate 86]]) in the [[Chautauqua County, New York|Chautauqua County]] town of [[Ellery, New York|Ellery]]. She had been shot four times: twice in the chest, once in the mouth and once in the back.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unsolved cases|url=http://www.sheriff.us/#!form/c21os|publisher=New York State Troopers}}</ref> The woman carried documents available in European countries and in Canada and had dental work appearing to use European techniques. The victim had brown eyes and graying brown hair, and was also estimated to have given birth to a child within the last 15 years. She was between 33 and 37 years of age when she had died, hours before being found. She was around {{convert|5|ft|4|in|cm}} tall and weighed around {{convert|128|lb}}. It is suspected that she may have been Canadian, as she carried a handwritten note with indecipherable abbreviations that originated from an establishment in [[British Columbia]]. She had some distinct characteristics: a wart was visible above her left eye, a mole was found behind the left ear and a scar was visible on her neck.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chautauqua New York Jane Doe December 1983|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/ChautauquaNewYorkJaneDoeDecember1983|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> The victim's clothing has caused some issues with determining her social class, as she wore both expensive and inexpensive clothing. The undershirt she wore originated from Italy and was not worth a lot of money. This product had also not been circulated globally. She also wore a multicolored trench coat that was fairly expensive, along with a pullover and a "handmade" skirt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 193UFNY|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/193ufny.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>
{{anchor|Putnam County John Doe}}
==Putnam County John Doe (1985)== {{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [https://content.troopers.ny.gov/getphoto.aspx?PhotoID=1F663F95-0F2A-47D8-A6B8-A65B8631BB0A Sketch] | image2 = [https://content.troopers.ny.gov/GetPhoto.aspx?PhotoID=d668d526-1875-4fb0-b0b5-a2335c8d0f5b 3D reconstruction] }}
On April 2, 1985, a man's remains were found nearly two years after his death, in Philipstown, Putnam County, New York. He was found with a dress shirt along with shorts, two pairs of pants with army coloring and corduroy material and work boots. Several pairs of underwear and socks were also found at the scene. A map of [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[New Jersey]], a comb, dental floss and [[playing card]]s were among his possessions. At one time in his life, he received orthodontic care.<ref name=decades>{{cite web| title=Decades Later, Who is this John Doe?| url=http://www.ctcoldcases.com/newyork.html| accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="New York State Troopers">{{cite web|title=Unidentified: Philipstown, Putnum County|url=https://www.troopers.ny.gov/Wanted_and_Missing/Unidentified/view.cfm?ID=82a82aa8-c260-4a94-936c-5d0f384b76fa&printer|publisher=New York State Troopers|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>
{{anchor|Westchester County Jane Doe (1988)}}
==Westchester County Jane Doe (1988)==
[[File:51UFNY Reconstruction Verson II (M).jpg|150px|thumb|Another reconstruction of the Westchester County Jane Doe]]
On February 14, 1988, the "posed" nude body of a woman was found on a street in Mount Vernon, Westchester County, New York. The victim had been dead for approximately six to twelve hours, and was bound at the wrists and ankles and had died from ligature strangulation as well as suffering a beating.<ref>{{cite web|title=Westchester New York Jane Doe February 1988|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/WestchesterNewYorkJaneDoeFebruary1988|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> She was aged 18 to 30, with hazel eyes and with bleached, light brown or blonde hair. She was 5 feet 3 inches tall, weighed 105 pounds, and had pierced ears without earrings. She had numerous freckles and moles (including a large and prominent mole on her neck). Her underarms had not been shaved for approximately two weeks, but her pubic area was recently shaved. This detail has led some investigators to presume she could have been a prostitute. The fact that the rest of the body showed an absence of shaving, it has also been suggested she was foreign to the United States, and could be of South American descent. Her nails were painted pink prior to her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 51UFNY|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/51ufny.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> No clothing was found at or near the scene.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 10229|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/10229|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=28 September 2014|date=3 May 2012}}</ref> An autopsy found that she had ingested cocaine and broccoli before her murder, which may have been the work of a serial offender.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=HELP CRIME WATCH DAILY AND CARL KOPPELMAN GIVE NAMES TO THESE 5 MURDER VICTIMS | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=10 October 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>
{{anchor|Irondequoit Jane Doe}}
==Irondequoit Jane Doe== {{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/sites/default/files/Monroe%20New%20York%20Jane%20Doe%20July%201988.jpg Sketch] }}
On July 31, 1988, a skeleton was found in a shallow grave by a boy who was digging at the edge of his family's property in [[Irondequoit]], [[Monroe County, New York]]. No signs of trauma were found, but the cause of death was ruled as a homicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 122UFNY|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/122ufny.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Unidentified: Town of Irondequoit, Monroe County, NY|url=http://www.troopers.ny.gov/Wanted_and_Missing/Unidentified/view.cfm?ID=6aa9b4ad-8e04-4ece-9f18-4c9fcb642d49|publisher=New york State Troopers|accessdate=18 August 2014|date=4 October 2000}}</ref>
The remains were those of a white female between 4 feet 10 inches and 5 feet 5 inches tall. Her weight, hair color, and eye color could not be determined.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monroe New York Jane Doe July 1988|url=http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/MonroeNewYorkJaneDoeJuly1988|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> She had significant dental restoration, which included gold foil fillings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1988|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1106805/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>
The victim, who was between 15 and 19 years of age, may have been deceased for as long as 10 to 30 years before being found .<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 2607|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/2607|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=18 August 2014|date=2 September 2008}}</ref> No clothing was found at the scene. A single white button, which may have belonged to the victim, was found near the remains.
==Long Island serial killer victims==
{{main|Long Island serial killer}}
The dismembered corpses of several females discovered between 1996 and present day.<ref name=decades/>
=="Peaches"==
{{main|Peaches (murder victim)}}
The torso of a woman found in 1997. She is known for her unique peach tattoo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.longislandpress.com/2010/07/01/long-islands-unidentified-murder-victims/|title=Long Island's Unidentified Murder Victims|work=Long Island Press|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> {{anchor|Woodbury John Doe}}
==Woodbury John Doe==
{{external media | align = | width = | image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1224544c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction] | image2 = [http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_mAfDIMyJweA/TGxRQLsyf2I/AAAAAAAABOQ/mjkr6yXOUJo/s1600/Charles+Doe+1998+NY+clothes.jpg Clothing] | image3 = [http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_mAfDIMyJweA/TGxSk1RQwFI/AAAAAAAABOg/j32EPe_4V1Q/s1600/Charles+Doe+1998+NY+facial+reconstruction.jpg Digital reconstruction] }}
On May 3, 1998, the skeleton of a black male was found in the [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]] town of [[Woodbury, Orange County, New York|Woodbury]]. He had been shot twice in the head by two guns of different calibers and left near a rest area for hikers. His body had been wrapped in plastic and he was fully clothed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 218UMNY|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/218umny.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> He carried a hair pick, a lighter and a French to English dictionary, indicating that he may have been from a Francophone country. Although the body was found in 1998, he was believed to have died as early as 1985. He was knock-kneed and between 5 feet 6 inches and 5 feet 11 inches in height, although he was more likely around five feet nine inches.<ref name=NCMECWoodbury>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1998|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1224544/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> He had been between seventeen and twenty-five years of age, but could have been as old as thirty-five.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unidentified: Town of Woodbury, Orange County, NY|url=http://www.troopers.ny.gov/Wanted_and_Missing/Unidentified/view.cfm?ID=caabac79-44f8-487d-9562-8eaac6247d02|publisher=New York State Troopers|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=22 September 1998}}</ref> He wore a blue jacket, a black shirt containing a pot of gold design with the words "follow your dreams," jeans and sneakers from the Pony company.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 9787|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/9787|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=18 August 2014|date=13 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Orange New York John Doe May 1998|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/OrangeNewYorkJohnDoeMay1998|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> He had had dental work, including fillings, crowns and a possible root canal. He had suffered a fracture of his right hand some weeks prior to death.<ref name=NCMECWoodbury/>
=="Cherries"== {{main|Cherries (murder victim)}}
A torso and pair of legs discovered in 2007. Like the torso found in 1997, dubbed "Peaches", she may have been a victim of the [[Long Island serial killer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.longislandpress.com/2010/07/01/long-islands-unidentified-murder-victims/cherry-tattoo/|title=Cherry Tattoo|work=Long Island Press|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref>
